uality? What role did the GULAG and prisons play in homosexuality across the USSR? These discussions often had practical implications – doctors designed and offered medical treatments for homosexuality in hospitals, and procedures and medications were also used in prisons.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 5, Gender equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay peoplexLegal status, laws, etc.zSoviet Union. 0aGaysxLegal status, laws, etczSoviet Union. 0aHomosexualityzSoviet Union. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aGULAG.  aGender equality.  aHistory of homosexuality.  aKhrushchev’s Thaw.  aLeonid Brezhnev.  aNikita Khrushchev.  aQueer history.  aSoviet history.  aSoviet legislation and homosexuality.  aSoviet prisons.  aSoviet sex education.  ahomosexuality in the USSR.  ahuman rights.  asexopathology.  astagnation.  astate repression.1 aAlexander, Rustam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615577140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526155771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526155771/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles